# Periodically re-disable EEE on eth0 in case something re-enables it.
#
# Why: the boot-time disable-eee OpenRC service (etc/init.d/disable-eee)
# turns EEE off once after dhcpcd brings the link up. That covers the
# common case, but the BCM54213PE PHY on the Pi 5 has been observed to
# re-enable EEE in the wild — typically after a kernel-driven link
# renegotiation, a dhcpcd renew that resets the PHY, or anything that
# triggers an mdio bus reinit. When that happens you get the classic
# 30-60-second link-flap loop until something disables EEE again.
#
# Why every 15 minutes: disable-eee is idempotent — when EEE is already
# off, eee-tool exits with "already off" without bouncing the link, so
# a periodic run costs nothing. Fifteen minutes bounds the worst-case
# flap window to a quarter hour without spamming logs.
#
# Why not a busier interval: when disable-eee DOES find EEE on and has
# to retry with -b (link bounce), the link drops for a moment, so we
# want to minimise the chance of stepping on a long-running transfer.
#
# NOTE on syntax: snooze uses `/N` (every N-th unit), NOT cron's `*/N`.
# `-M */15` parses as `-M *` and fires every minute.  Also: without an
# `-H` flag, snooze defaults to hour 0 (midnight only).  `-H /1` means
# every hour.  Verified with `snooze -nv -H /1 -M /15 -S 0` listing the
# next fires :00, :15, :30, :45 across every hour.
SNOOZE_ARGS="-H /1 -M /15 -S 0"
COMMAND="/bin/disable-eee eth0"
